  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is it possible to use Python to write a script for Google Drive?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to use Python to write a script that interacts with Google Drive. You can use the Google Drive API to perform various operations such as uploading files, downloading files, listing files, and managing your drive in general. Here is a general outline of how you can do this:\n\n1. **Set Up Google Credentials:**\n   - Go to the Google Developers Console.\n   - Create a new project.\n   - Enable the Google Drive API for your project.\n   - Create credentials (OAuth 2.0 client ID) for a desktop application.\n   - Download the `credentials.json` file.\n\n2. **Install Required Libraries:**\n   - Use pip to install the `google-auth`, `google-auth-oauthlib`, `google-auth-httplib2`, and `google-api-python-client` libraries.\n   \n   ```bash\n   pip install google-auth google-auth-oauthlib google-auth-httplib2 google-api-python-client\n   ```\n\n3. **Write the Python Script:**\n   - Use the following basic script to authenticate and perform actions on Google Drive:\n\n   ```python\n   from __future__ import print_function\n   import os.path\n   from google.oauth2.credentials import Credentials\n   from google_auth_oauthlib.flow import InstalledAppFlow\n   from google.auth.transport.requests import Request\n   from googleapiclient.discovery import build\n\n   # If modifying these SCOPES, delete the file token.json.\n   SCOPES = ['https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive.metadata.readonly']\n\n   def main():\n       \"\"\"Shows basic usage of the Drive v3 API.\n       Prints the names and ids of the first 10 files the user has access to.\n       \"\"\"\n       creds = None\n       # The file token.json stores the user's access and refresh tokens, and is\n       # created automatically when the authorization flow completes for the first\n       # time.\n       if os.path.exists('token.json'):\n           creds = Credentials.from_authorized_user_file('token.json', SCOPES)\n       # If there are no (valid) credentials available, let the user log in.\n       if not creds or not creds.valid:\n           if creds and creds.expired and creds.refresh_token:\n               creds.refresh(Request())\n           else:\n               flow = InstalledAppFlow.from_client_secrets_file(\n                   'credentials.json', SCOPES)\n               creds = flow.run_local_server(port=0)\n           # Save the credentials for the next run\n           with open('token.json', 'w') as token:\n               token.write(creds.to_json())\n\n       try:\n           # Call the Drive v3 API\n           service = build('drive', 'v3', credentials=creds)\n           results = service.files().list(\n               pageSize=10, fields=\"nextPageToken, files(id, name)\").execute()\n           items = results.get('files', [])\n\n           if not items:\n               print('No files found.')\n           else:\n               print('Files:')\n               for item in items:\n                   print(u'{0} ({1})'.format(item['name'], item['id']))\n       except Exception as error:\n           print(f'An error occurred: {error}')\n\n   if __name__ == '__main__':\n       main()\n   ```\n\n4. **Run the Script:**\n   - Ensure you have both `credentials.json` and `token.json` in your working directory.\n   - Run the script using Python.\n\nPlease note that the Google Drive API has extensive capabilities, and depending on what you need to do (upload, delete files, etc.), you may need to adjust the scopes of access accordingly. Always be cautious with credentials and manage them securely.",
